<br>
When my mom died, I said straight out that I would not go to any viewing and we opted for closed casket. We had only one picture of her among the forest of flowers that had been sent.<br>
<br>
Well, the evening of the viewing, the night before the service, my sister's were going to be there. They went and when they say my mom's body, they burst out laughing because it didn't look like her at all. The hair was wrong, the makeup was ridiculous, etc, etc.. They called me and said I HAD to come because it really helped them to know that Mom wasn't <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>there</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.. So, I agreed and when I got there, they were redoing the hair. There was my one sister hanging over the body going &quot;Mom! They've made you up like a clown! We're going to fix you up&quot; When she went to fix the lipstick, because of the imbalming, the mouth went wacky.. and it stayed. So, that led to more laughter. (I'm sure the folks thought we were all drunk or on drugs or just plain crazy) Finally, after working the mouth back into a semblance of what her's looked like, my mom's body was what we deemed &quot;acceptable&quot;.. and we got ready for the people to show up. After, I could honestly say it DID help. Of course, we know where she is, and we will see her again some day.<br>
<br>
Then next day, at the actual funeral, we all were missing her horribly.. but thankfully, we'd given the pastor her Bible. He was able to make a wonderful service. NO one left that building not hearing the Gospel. That was her wish... and she got it BIG TIME. <br>
<br>
After there was a reception at the church. EVERYone shared stories about how Mom had touched their life. I think we went through 6 boxes of tissue.<br>
<br>
Then, those that are close family and friends went to my Dad's, where we all were staying. We were up the whole night talking and remembering and laughing and crying. <br>
<br>
And, now some 3½ years later, we still have our &quot;Mommy Moments&quot;. I can't get through the hymns anymore. I just stand there and cry. But, that day... oh my gosh... she gave us <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>another</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> memory.<br>
<br>
