<br>
Whenever the subject came up. the rare times I've been <br>
asked how I'd like my corpus treated, I have said the following:<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;I wish to be cremated, mixed with tobacco, and smoked by<br>
my closest friends.&quot;<br>
<br>
This invariably silenced the room, especially since I said it <br>
with a deadpan delivery. <br>
<br>
Inasmuch as I know there are sick people out there who<br>
fiddle with corpses, I'd prefer a cremation to anything else.<br>
I know some people who have religious objections to it,<br>
but I'm not aware of any Biblical injunction against it.<br>
Some people have said things about the resurrection, but I<br>
figure that God won't run out of power reconstituting me.<br>
<br>
That didn't address the question, though.<br>
<br>
I'd rather be remembered as I was ALIVE, rather than as a<br>
dead body.  I understand some people get a sense of closure<br>
seeing the body, so I suppose that's fine.  I like the idea of<br>
pictures and remembrances up as well.  I've said that I'd <br>
hope somebody'd be sorry to see me go, so they'd shed a <br>
tear, but I'd also hope that someone would really remember<br>
me, and laugh as well.  I've even toyed with the idea of<br>
hiring a comedian to ensure that, but I concluded it would<br>
just come off crass. <br>
<br>
I've heard of even worse ideas, though...and had a few.<br>
<br>
I STILL don't get calling it a &quot;wake&quot;, when if that actually<br>
